{{Person|磯城皇子}} {{Infobox Imperial Family Member | name = Prince Kawashima | image = | image_size = | caption = | period = [[Asuka period]] | birth_date = 3rd year of [[Empress Saimei]] (657) | death_date = | demise = 5th year of [[Empress Jitō]], 9th day of the 9th month (October 6, 691) | other_names = Prince Kawashima (河島皇子) | posthumous_name = | honorific_title = | dharma_name = | resting_place = | court_Rank = Jōdaisan (浄大参) | parents = Father: [[:en:Emperor Tenji|Emperor Tenji]]; Mother: {{ill|Onokami no Shoryu's daughter|ja|忍海小竜娘|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onokami no Shoryu's daughter|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} | siblings = [[Emperor Kōbun]], [[Prince Take]], Prince Kawashima, [[Prince Shiki]], [[Princess Ōta]], [[Empress Jitō]], [[Princess Minabe]], [[Empress Genmei]], [[Princess Yamabe]], [[Princess Asuka]], [[Princess Nittabe]], [[Princess Ōe]], [[Princess Izumi]], [[Princess Mizushi]], among others | spouse = [[Princess Hasebe]] | children = [[Prince Kasuga (son of Prince Kawashima)|Prince Kasuga]], [[Prince Mimuro]], [[Prince Takaoka]] | notable_achievements = }}
'''Prince Kawashima''' (川島皇子, also 河島皇子) was the second son of [[:en:Emperor Tenji|Emperor Tenji]]<ref name="s">*{{cite book|title=[[Kaifūsō]]|year=8th century}}</ref>. He held the court Rank of Jōdaisan (浄大参) and was the progenitor of clans such as the {{ill|Ōmi no Asomi|ja|淡海朝臣|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi no Asomi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and the {{ill|Harahara no Asomi|ja|春原朝臣|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Harahara no Asomi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.
== Career == Prince Kawashima was married to [[Princess Hasebe]], the daughter of [[:en:Emperor Tenmu|Emperor Tenmu]]. In the 8th year of Emperor Tenmu’s reign (679), he participated in the [[Oath of Yoshino]], a ceremony pledging loyalty to the emperor alongside other imperial princes such as [[Prince Kusakabe]], [[Prince Ōtsu]], [[Prince Takatsu]], [[Prince Osakabe]], and [[Prince Shiki]]<ref>''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', entry for the 8th year of Emperor Tenmu, 5th month, 6th day</ref>. In the 10th year (681), Prince Kawashima was ordered to assist in compiling the "Records of the Sovereigns and Various Events of Antiquity" (帝紀及び上古諸事), a monumental task of national historiography<ref>''Nihon Shoki'', entry for the 10th year of Emperor Tenmu, 3rd month, 17th day</ref>.
In the 14th year of Emperor Tenmu’s reign (685), Prince Kawashima attained the Rank of Jōdaisan. Among the imperial princes, his status was surpassed only by [[Prince Kusakabe]] (Jōkōichi), [[Prince Ōtsu]] (Jōdaichi), and [[Prince Takatsu]] (Jōkōni)<ref>''Nihon Shoki'', entry for the 14th year of Emperor Tenmu, 1st month, 21st day</ref>. In Shuchō 1 (686), following Emperor Tenmu's death, Prince Kawashima received an additional 100 households as a stipend, bringing his total to 500 households, a Rank comparable to leading officials of the court<ref>''Nihon Shoki'', entry for the 5th year of Empress Jitō, 1st month, 13th day</ref>. He passed away later that year and was interred at Ochi-no in present-day [[Takaichi District]], [[Nara Prefecture]].
== Legacy == Prince Kawashima is remembered as a warm and magnanimous individual. His involvement in the [[Prince Ōtsu]] incident has been debated, with some sources suggesting he reported Ōtsu’s alleged rebellion to the court. However, the ''Nihon Shoki'' does not corroborate this, leading scholars to question its veracity<ref>Tokura Yoshitaka, "Prince Ōtsu and His Surroundings," ''Manyōshū Lecture Series'', Vol. 5, Yūseidō, 1973</ref>.
Both the ''[[Kaifūsō]]'' and the ''[[Manyōshū]]'' contain works attributed to him, showcasing his talent in poetry and literature. The ''Kaifūsō'' includes one Chinese-style [[wuyan jueju]] poem, while the ''Manyōshū'' features a single Japanese waka attributed to him during [[Empress Jitō]]'s 4th-year tour to [[Kii Province]] and [[Ise Province]]<ref>''Manyōshū'', Vol. 1-34</ref>.
== Works == The ''Manyōshū'' contains an elegy by [[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]] for Prince Kawashima<ref>''Manyōshū'', Vol. 2-194, 195</ref>.
* Elegy presented to Princess Hasebe upon Prince Kawashima's death: ** "Like the seaweed on the u11er reaches of the river Asuka, it sways and intertwines. My lord, whose soft skin I embraced, cannot lie by my side with sword in hand. The night-bed is cold, and I wander alone, wet with morning dew on the fields of Ochi, where we cannot meet again." * [[Tanka]]: ** "The sleeves of our shared bed lie forgotten in Ochi’s fields. Shall we ever meet again?"
== Genealogy == * Father: [[:en:Emperor Tenji|Emperor Tenji]] * Mother: {{ill|Onokami no Shoryu's daughter|ja|忍海色夫古娘|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onokami no Shoryu's daughter|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} ''' Siblings: [[Princess Ōe]], [[Princess Izumi]] * Wife: [[Princess Hasebe]]<ref name=":0">{{cite book|title=Manyōshū, Vol. 2}}</ref> * Children: ** [[Prince Kasuga (son of Prince Kawashima)|Prince Kasuga]] (?-699)<ref>Shioya Kaori, "Doubts about the Genealogy of Prince Shiki," ''Gakushūin Journal'', Vol. 23, 1980</ref> ** [[Prince Mimuro]] (?-745)<ref name="h">{{cite book|author=Suzuki Masatoshi|title=Hundred Family Genealogies, Vol. 10}}</ref> ** [[Prince Takaoka]] (?-749)<ref name="h" />
== References == {{reflist}}
== Bibliography == * Ujitani, Takeru. ''Nihon Shoki (Lower Volume): Full Modern Translation.'' Kodansha Academic, 1988. * Hoga, Toshio. ''Compilation of Ancient Clan Genealogies.'' Research Group on Ancient Clans, 1986.
